what: Find the appropriate number of breaks using Jenks natural breaks optimization — get_breaks_num
title: Find the appropriate number of breaks using Jenks natural breaks optimization — get_breaks_num
text: function optimizes number breaks given dataset using Jenks natural breaks algorithm. iterates different numbers breaks calculates Goodness Variance Fit (GVF) combination individual time point. GVF metric helps determine number breaks best represents data structure minimizing variance within groups.

title: Find the appropriate number of breaks using Jenks natural breaks optimization — get_breaks_num
Find the appropriate number of breaks using Jenks natural breaks optimization — get_breaks_num
text: social_networks 3D array containing social network data time. Dimensions individuals (first/second dimension), time points (third dimension). max_breaks maximum number breaks consider. Default 5.

title: Find the appropriate number of breaks using Jenks natural breaks optimization — get_breaks_num
text: data frame containing GVF values different numbers breaks across individuals time points.

title: Find the appropriate number of breaks using Jenks natural breaks optimization — get_breaks_num
code: # Example usage: # Assuming 'social_network_data' is a 3D array with dimensions # [individuals, individuals, time] social_network_data <- data(zf_rep1_real) result <- get_breaks_num(social_network_data, max_breaks = 5) # Explore the results to determine the optimal number of breaks

what: Calculate the GVF metric (Goodness of Variance Fit) — gvf
title: Calculate the GVF metric (Goodness of Variance Fit) — gvf
text: function computes GVF metric, measures goodness fit observed data classification predefined groups using Jenks breaks. calculates proportion variance explained grouped data compared original data.

title: Calculate the GVF metric (Goodness of Variance Fit) — gvf
Calculate the GVF metric (Goodness of Variance Fit) — gvf
text: data numeric vector observed values. num_breaks integer specifying number groups classify data .

title: Calculate the GVF metric (Goodness of Variance Fit) — gvf
text: GVF metric value, ranges 0 1. higher value indicates better fit.

title: Calculate the GVF metric (Goodness of Variance Fit) — gvf
code: # Example usage: data <- rnorm(100, mean = 0, sd = 1) # Generate a numeric vector gvf_result <- gvf(data, num_breaks = 5) # Output the result

title: Calculate Multilevel Group Size from Social Networks — multilevel_group_size
code: # Example usage: # Assuming 'social_network_data' is a 3D array with dimensions # [individuals, individuals, time] social_network_data <- data(zf_rep1_real) group_sizes <- multilevel_group_size(social_network_data) print(group_sizes) #> data frame with 0 columns and 0 rows
